NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Angie, you heard mark bid 2@S, so you must keep all your spades because you know he has a 4-card suit. Yes, dummy has 4 hearts and might be able to run hearts if you pitch a heart, but you have to hope partner can stop hearts. On the other hand, you know for sure declarer has 4 spades and if you pitch a spade you will be setting up the 4th spade.|
PG| ***** 156 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Remember, the auction often gives you clues about how to defend. You should try and take advantage of those clues when you can. Many players forget about the auction once the play starts. That is a big mistake. Remembering the auction often provides critical clues as to how to best play and defend. Next I will comment on the bidding.|
PG| ***** 157 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Bernean has a perfectly reasonable 2@C bid and many players would bid 2@C. But I am trying to teach you to be better than average :). Let me explain why I think there are better alternatives. |
PG| ***** 158 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Some people suggested you are strong enough to double and correct. They are technically correct, but I will explain why I don't think that is the best action. In fact, I think it is not as good an alternative as 2@C.|
PG| ***** 159 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Once partner passes, it is unlikely your side can make 5@C. So why not just get your clubs in right away, bid 3@C, so at least if partner is on lead she will know what to lead. I suggest you should bid 3@C with your hand. Your partner is a passed hand, therefore, you want to be as obstructive as possible.|
PG| ***** 160 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|From your perspective, they could easily have a major suit fit, especially spades, but possibly even hearts. So, given your partner passed, it is right to preempt. It is the same reasoning as why you should sometimes open a preempt in 3rd seat even if you have a real 1-level opener. You are unlikely to be missing game. |
PG| ***** 161 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|There is no harm in partner thinking you are slightly weaker than you are. As long as you both use the law of total tricks to decide how to bid, preempting after partner passes, even with a minimum opener, is often a good tactic. Some people are concerned that if you preempt with a strong hand that should be alertable.|
PG| ***** 162 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|But it is not alertable. so long as your agreement is that it shows a weak hand, you can preempt with a strong hand so long as partner assumes you have a weak hand. In fact, most experts will use the tactic of preempting even with opening hands when they have a long suit and partner has passed. It is a well understood tactic.|
PG| ***** 163 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|On another point, when partner opens 1 of a minor and later rebids a major (as on this hand), it is virtually certain they only have a 4-card suit in the major. It is important to keep that in mind. Yes, very rarely they will have a 5-card major and 6-card minor, but that happens so infrequently that it is not worth worrying about.|
PG| ***** 164 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward Schutzman: ^*N|cp||at|Therefore, always assume when partner opens a minor and rebids a major, the major is 4 cards. You will be right 99% of the time, and if you are not right, partner will let you know anyway.|
PG| ***** 165 ***** |


